<TEXT>
congress is trying to move the issues of 
affordable housing and homelessness to the forefront of the national 
agenda after eight years of cutbacks under the reagan 
administration 
more than a quarter of the senate last week cosponsored a bill 
that seeks to address the housing concerns of everyone from 
firsttime home buyers to the homeless 
the bill called the national affordable housing act seeks to 
set the framework for a new national housing strategy said sen 
alan cranston dcalif chairman of the banking housing and urban 
affairs subcommittee on housing 
it is imperative that we reverse a decade of neglect in 
housing i sense a growing impatience to raise housing back to 
the place it deserves in the nations priorities said cranston 
the bills primary sponsor 
the act would require states and local governments to submit 
fiveyear housing plans to the department of housing and urban 
development and update the plans annually it also would create a 
single institution within hud with the authority to provide direct 
assistance to government agencies 
it would establish an assistant housing secretary post to 
administer programs for the elderly handicapped and homeless 
for individuals the bill would seek to reduce the size of down 
payments and allow firsttime home buyers to use funds from 
individual retirement accounts or 401k retirement plans for the 
investment reduce fha mortgage rates while increasing the ceiling 
of loan amounts in many cases and set limits on the percentage of 
income paid by tenants receiving rental assistance 
lowincome tax credits for developers set to expire next year 
would be made permanent through provisions set forth in an earlier 
bill cosponsored by senate majority leader george mitchell of maine 
and sen john danforth rmo 
there have been no specific commitments from the bush 
administration but housing secretary jack kemp likes many of the 
bills elements is very interested in the measure according to 
cranston who has met with kemp several times 
were going to enact housing legislation this session 
declared mitchell 
the subcommittee will begin hearings on the proposal next month 
as the cranston bill came out of the senate rep henry gonzalez 
dtexas chairman of the house subcommittee on housing and community 
development held the second in a series of allday hearings on the 
need for permanent housing for the homeless 
earlier in the month sen al gore dtenn challenged bush to 
show the leadership this issue demands and called for a white 
house conference on homelessness 
in addition sen barbara mikulski dmd is set to challenge 
the bush administration if it intends to replace rental assistance 
certificates with vouchers as proposed in former president reagans 
budget 
mikulski has released a study by the general accounting office 
the research arm of congress which presents compelling evidence 
that the administrations housing voucher program will cost as much 
as 96 billion more over the next 12 years than the rental 
assistance certificate program it was designed to replace 
and rep tom lantos dcalif said kemp has agreed to appear 
before the government operations subcommittee on employment and 
housing which lantos chairs kemps appearance would follow his 
expected selection as chairman of the interagency council for the 
homeless 
the council the governments chief coordinating agency for 
homelessness programs was roundly criticized by lawmakers last week 
as a donothing panel under reagan 
