began his annual rite of ringing the mission courtyard bells on 
schedule on sunday which also marked the 50th anniversary of leon 
renes 1939 song when the swallows come back to capistrano 
for the air fare that i paid from new york i wanted swarms 
said colleen dunnholzworth 21 of new york city a rutgers 
university student spending spring break in southern california 
television camera crews eager for the proper dramatic effect 
resorted to throwing pebbles at the mission walls to get the already 
nesting birds to take flight 
although bird watchers say the swallows now roost throughout the 
sprawling orange county community tourists swarmed to the mission 
area and to nearby gift shops 
this year the first of the birds reached southern california in 
february said sandy wohlgemuth of the audubon society los angeles 
first accounts of the swallows coming from south america to san 
juan capistrano date to 1776 the year father junipero serra founded 
the picturesque mission as part of spains effort to colonize the 
new world 
mission museum director nick magalousis said the birds numbers 
at the mission have dwindled in recent years as they choose new 
sites to roost 
the main place thats most obvious is the mission viejo mall 
he said referring to a nearby shopping center theres hundreds 
of nests over there 
