<TEXT>
the farm chemical alar has for four years been 
a symbol of industrial arrogance and regulatory footdragging to 
followers of the consumer movement 
but despite activists efforts its a safe bet most americans 
knew little or nothing about alar which is used to grow crisper 
more colorful apples and which has been linked to cancer in animal 
tests 
thats changed dramatically in the last two weeks 
the alarapple debate quickly gained publicpolicy star status 
through a 60 minutes television report the involvement of 
actress meryl streep and surprise moves by educators in new york and 
los angeles to yank apples from school lunchrooms 
despite reassurances from the government and health establishment 
that alar isnt all that unsafe signs of alarm have mounted 
by the end of last week the heads of the environmental 
protection agency and the food and drug administration both felt 
compelled to defend the nations apple supply they were joined by 
surgeon general c everett koop who released a statement saturday 
saying i wish to send a message to mothers across the country 
its ok mom apples are good for your kids 
apple growers in washington state blamed the controversy for a 
drop of nearly 10 percent in shipments of apples out of state in two 
weeks 
grocers and apple processing companies across the country 
reiterated policies against accepting apples sprayed with alar 
meanwhile the manufacturer of the chemical uniroyal chemical co 
of middlebury conn has repeatedly cited research showing alar in 
the concentrations found in apples doesnt pose a cancer threat 
the alar debate has been around with varying degrees of fervor 
since august 1985 when the epa considered but rejected a ban on the 
chemical used to control ripening and improve quality consistency 
and shelf life of apples 
in early february the epa finally did propose a phaseout of use 
of the chemical which would take it off the market starting 
probably next year but the epa said the threat of alar was not so 
severe that the ban had to start right away 
consumer groups including ralph naders public citizens health 
research group and the national resources defense council have 
campaigned for an immediate ban instead 
the periodic consumer campaigns have prompted many big 
supermarket chains and apple processors across the country to quit 
accepting alartreated apples as a result use of the chemical fell 
to an estimated 5 percent to 10 percent of the crop from a high 
around 50 percent many growers hoped controversy was behind them 
but on feb 26 the dormant controversy erupted anew 
the cbs television show 60 minutes reported a study by the 
natural resources group suggesting children because of low body 
weight and proportionately high consumption of apples had a 
heightened risk of cancer from alar 
then miss streep appeared on tv talk shows and gave interviews 
about her fears for her three childrens health 
the resulting blast of publicity prompted officials in the 
nations two biggest school districts new york and los angeles to 
temporarily pull apples and apple products from their cafeterias 
reports of the apple bans quickly spread 
in our democratic process an angry mob will be listened to no 
matter what the facts are said mark helmke a washington dc 
consultant with the robinson lake lerer and montgomery public 
relations firm 
thats whats happened in this case this story has struck a 
nerve helmke said 
studies show alar a trade name for the chemical daminozide 
could be linked to cancer in laboratory animals a breakdown product 
of alar called udmh also was shown to cause cancer when give to test 
animals in large amounts 
the american academy of pediatrics adopted a position paper march 
11 calling for an end to alar use but said parents shouldnt worry 
about farm chemicals applied in legal amounts 
</TEXT>
