ten people criminally convicted for their 
participation in a 1985 protest demonstration at a philadelphia 
abortion clinic lost a supreme court appeal today 
the justices without comment refused to hear arguments that the 
defendants wrongly were barred from asserting medical justification 
as a defense for their crimes 
the appeal also urged that the philadelphia case be used to 
reverse the high courts 1973 decision legalizing abortion 
the justices already have under study an abortionregulation 
dispute from missouri in which they are being asked to reverse or 
limit the 16yearold ruling in a case called roe vs wade 
in the philadelphia case the 10 were convicted of defiant 
trespass and acquitted of all other charges stemming from an aug 
10 1985 antiabortion demonstration at the northeast womens 
center 
a state appeals court said the 10 pushed their way into the 
clinic and occupied several rooms once inside they damaged two 
aspirator machines and other medical instruments threw equipment 
out of a thirdfloor window and placed prolife stickers on the 
doors walls and ceilings the state court said 
after refusing to leave the 10 protesters were carried away by 
police officers 
each drew a sentence of one day to three months in jail 
a state appeals court upheld the convictions and sentences last 
may 2 and the pennsylvania supreme court refused to hear their 
appeal last oct 20 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the 10 protesters said 
their clients are among thousands of lawabiding citizens now 
engaging in heightened demonstrations or rescues at abortion 
clinics throughout the united states 
the appeal said that each of the protesters knew that his or 
her conduct would otherwise be criminal except for the defense of 
justification sought to be interposed in this case 
the appeal was filed in behalf of roland markum john obrien 
howard walton susan silcox kathy long ellen jones anne marie 
breen henry tenagolio joseph wall and walter gies 
the case is markum vs pennsylvania 881218 
