<TEXT>
a floridabased company wanting to require all 
its employees to attend weekly christian devotional services lost a 
supreme court appeal today 
the justices without comment left intact rulings that the 
requirement violated the rights of an atheist who worked at the 
companys plant in eloy ariz 
lawyers for the company argued that its owners constitutionally 
protected religious freedoms were violated 
unless employers may operate their businesses in 
accordance with their sincerely held religious beliefs the private 
workplace will increasingly become void of religion the appeal 
contended 
jo jake and helen townley control and manage the townley 
manufacturing co based in candler fla 
the couple are bornagain christians who said they promised god 
their miningequipment manufacturing company would be a christian 
faithoperated business 
the company founded in florida in 1963 since has opened other 
plants including one in eloy ariz 
employees at townley plants for years were required to attend 
weekly devotional services 
louis pelvas identified in court documents as an atheist began 
working as a machinist at the townley plant in eloy in 1979 
mandatory attendance at devotional services was not required there 
until 1984 
pelvas attended several and then asked to be excused because he 
was an atheist his supervisor told pelvas that he had to attend but 
that he could sleep read a newspaper or otherwise engage himself 
durng the services 
pelvas continued to attend the services which usually lasted 30 
to 45 minutes during the work day but in october 1984 he filed a 
religiousdiscrimination complaint with the federal equal employment 
opportunity commission pelvas left the company two months later 
saying he was offered a transfer that amounted to a firing 
the commission in 1986 ruled that townley violated a part of the 
civil rights act of 1964 barring onthejob religious discrimination 
a federal trial judge in arizona barred townley in may 1987 from 
continuing mandatory devotional services at the eloy plant 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals upheld the judges 
injunction last oct 20 
the appeals court noted that the federal law imposes a duty on 
employers to accommodate an employees religious practices unless 
doing so would cause undue hardship 
the appeals court said townley had failed to prove any undue 
hardship in pelvas case and rejected the companys argument that 
it is a religious corporation congress intended to exempt from 
the law 
the eeoc does not seek to enjoin the services altogether 
rather it only objects to their mandatory nature the appeals 
court said 
the bush administration urged the court to rule against townley 
and its owners 
any minor burden on the townleys religious practices is 
justified in this case government lawyers said 
the case is townley manufacturing co vs eeoc 88988 
</TEXT>
