ucla a california staterun university illegally copied a 
companys computer programs and instruction manuals 
the justices on feb 21 turned away a similar appeal by a 
photographer who accused a state university in virginia of 
unauthorized use of his photographs 
in the case acted on today bv engineerings appeal was supported 
by numerous members of the artistic entertainment and literary 
community 
nine major motion picture studios urged the court to hear bv 
engineerings appeal to broaden protection against what they said is 
widespread copyright infringement 
the movie producers said for example that prisons in kansas 
west virginia idaho utah delaware north carolina and rhode 
island are refusing to pay for films shown to inmates 
bv engineering sued ucla in 1986 accusing the university of 
illegally copying seven computer programs and the accompanying user 
manuals 
the suit was thrown out by a federal judge and the 9th us 
circuit court of appeals ruled last october that states and state 
agencies are immune from copyrightinfringement suits 
the appeals court said states are protected by the constitutions 
11th amendment which shields them from a variety of lawsuits 
the appeals court citing previous supreme court rulings said 
the federal copyright act of 1976 does not explicitly remove or 
abrogate the 11th amendment protection 
we are constrained by the supreme courts mandate that we find 
an abrogation of 11th amendment immunity only when congress has 
included in the statute unequivocal and specific language indicating 
an intent to subject states to suit in federal court the 9th 
circuit court said 
we recognize that our holding will allow states to violate the 
federal copyright laws with virtual impunity the appeals court 
continued it is for congress however to remedy this problem 
bv engineering said it was left without a remedy since federal 
copyright law bars the company from suing ucla in state court in 
california 
the case is bv engineering vs ucla 881099 
