abc television correspondent david 
brinkley and retired associated press international correspondent 
and bureau chief morris rosenberg are among the nine men who will be 
inducted into the north carolina journalism advertising and public 
relations halls of fame april 9 
brinkley a native of wilmington nc began his journalism 
career as a high school student writing for the wilmington star he 
got his first fulltime broadcasting job with nbc news in 1943 he 
stayed with nbc until 1981 when he moved to abc 
rosenberg a native of charlotte nc is a 1940 graduate of the 
university of north carolina school of journalism he served as a 
correspondent for the associated press in venezuela and as an editor 
for ap world services in new york 
he was bureau chief in paris from 1966 to 1977 then directed 
aps latin american bureaus he headed aps world service operations 
in the washington bureau from 1979 until his retirement in 1987 
others who will be inducted into the hall of fame include john b 
adams former dean of the unc school of journalism david gillespie 
former editorial page editor of the charlotte observer the late 
brodie griffith former editor of the charlotte news and jim 
shumaker associate professor of journalism at unc and former editor 
of the chapel hill newspaper 
the unc school of journalism started the journalism hall of fame 
in 1981 since then 39 journalists with ties to north carolina have 
been inducted including tom wicker vermont royster and charles 
kuralt 
