a federal judge today stopped the district of 
columbia from enforcing the citys new emergency curfew law for 
teenagers 
after a hearing on a suit brought by the american civil liberties 
union us district judge charles richey issued a 10day temporary 
restraining order blocking enforcement of the statute in issuing 
his ruling the judge said the law was too broad 
he noted that mayor marion barry jr has said alternative 
legislation will be proposed to narrow the law 
richey said he would extend the restraining order if barrys 
legislation does not differ from the emergency bill reviewed today 
barrys revised measure is expected to go to the city council on 
tuesday or next week 
the law went into effect last thursday but barry delayed 
enforcement of the measure until monday night to give police time to 
become familiar with its provisions and to inform the public 
aclu attorney arthur spitzer said the law would penalize youths 
and also could give them a permanent legal record 
city attorneys however argued that parents would be penalized 
but richey noted that the students names would be entered into a 
permanent police record which might affect their ability to get jobs 
the aclu filed suit on friday to declare the temporary 90day 
law unconstitutional 
