<TEXT>
poison specialists on monday demonstrated a new 
childresistant medicine cap they hope will solve the problem of 
caps that are too difficult for the elderly to open 
in ceremonies marking the opening of national poison prevention 
week anne graham the acting chairman of the consumer product 
safety commission noted that roughly half the accidental medical 
poisonings of children under age 5 were from childresistant 
packages that had not been properly resecured or from nonchild 
resistance containers holding medicines originally packed in 
childresistant containers 
child poisonings have declined greatly with the advent of the 
childresistant caps from 216 deaths of children under 5 in 1972 to 
59 in 1986 
nonethess ms graham noted studies show that 35 percent of the 
medicines ingested in childpoisoning cases come from people not in 
the immediate family most frequently grandparents 
like the present mechanism the new cap device has an inner and 
outer cap that lock together when the outer cap is pressed down on 
the inner cap 
unlike the present design the inner and outer caps of the new 
mechanism each has a small slot across part of a diameter when the 
slots are aligned a spoon handle may be inserted into both to make 
the two caps turn together using the spoon as a lever without 
downward pressure on the outer cap 
this is our first effort said robert wygant professor of 
industrial engineering at western michigan university in kalamazoo 
at the news conference at the national capital poison control center 
at georgetown university hospital we have many other tests to 
do 
wygant developed the prototype cap from a design by professor 
hugh lockhart of michigan state university 
the design emerged from earlier work by western michigan 
university michigan state university and the university of 
wisconsin 
wygant who estimated that more than a billion caps are made for 
medicine alone every year said that among other problems to be 
solved was the production of clear instructions and making the caps 
easy to manufacture 
commission spokesmen said the commission plans to require use of 
the caps or something similar once all the bugs are worked out 
