<TEXT>
diplomats and ministers from 111 
nations met monday for a unsponsored toxic waste conference to 
culminate in a treaty regulating international trafficking of 
dangerous products 
but african delegations demanded alterations in the 51page draft 
document and threatened to stall the threeday meeting 
if approved the treaty formally gives all signing countries the 
right to refuse imports of hazardous wastes and requires exporters 
to provide prospective recipients details of shipments 
signatories will pledge to dispose of dangerous waste in an 
environmentally sound way and also will commit to keep international 
toxic waste traffic to a minimum 
mostafa tolba executive director of the united nations 
environment program said international hazardous waste trade is 
threatening public health and the environment 
at least 100000 shipments of toxic waste crosses international 
borders annually in a commerce of poison worth billions of 
dollars tolba told delegates at the opening session 
tolba said the basel treaty would signal the end of uncontrolled 
hazardous waste transport 
but malis environment minister morifing kone speaking for the 
organization of african unity said the treaty contains gaps he 
said some african nations want a guarantee that industrialized 
countries wont use developing areas as a dumping ground for 
poisonous wastes 
greenpeace the international environmental group on monday 
criticized the treaty for not covering radioactive waste and 
allowing member countries to sign waste trade pacts with nonmember 
nations 
the problem of international trafficking in dangerous wastes was 
dramatized last year when several waste shipments from 
industrialized countries were found dumped in african nations 
including nigeria and guinea wasteladen ships traveled from port 
to port looking for a place to dispose of their cargo 
environmentalists said they were concerned that importing toxic 
waste had become a source of income for poor countries with no safe 
disposal plans 
europes attention was drawn to the problem earlier when barrels 
of toxic waste from italys seveso chemical plant spill vanished in 
1982 before turning up months later in france the incident led to 
the adoption of european community rules on crossborder dangerous 
waste transport 
</TEXT>
