<TEXT>
victoria burton 11 shivering in a cold wind 
on the first day of spring sang the national anthem at an empty 
robert f kennedy stadium better than three other children and 29 
adults monday and won the right to sing it again with the sun 
presumably warmer and the stands fuller 
the girl from the baltimore suburb of cockeysville won an 
audition to sing the starspangled banner on april 2 the day 
before the baseball season begins for real at an exhibition game 
between the baltimore orioles and the st louis cardinals two 
foreign teams named after birds 
the nations capital has been without a team since the second set 
of senators headed west to dallasfort worth in 1972 that version 
of the senators had been created as an expansion club by baseballs 
rulers in 1961 to fill the void when the first senators skipped town 
for minneapolis 
victoria wearing a bow in her hair and braces on her teeth said 
she was nervous but not at all worried about forgetting the words 
she said she had known the words by heart for years 
her mother sarah burton said victoria started singing even 
before she learned to walk 
she recalled that when victoria was in the second grade her 
teacher called and said ive got to talk to you about your 
daughter 
i thought shed done something terrible mrs burton said 
but when i went to school he said shes got this remarkable 
voice weve got to do something about it 
victoria joined the maryland childrens chorus she also sings at 
dinner theaters and her mother said at every opportunity 
for several hours the national anthem echoed in the empty 
stadium contestants sat in highpriced seats along the first base 
line awaiting the chance to stand at a microphone behind home plate 
and sing 
among them were mike ferraro 57 needing a shave just off the 
nightshift at the merrifield va post office who carried the 
words on a card in his pocket just in case my mind went blank 
ed strude an air conditioning refrigeration combusion engineer who 
sings in the choir of the district heights md first bapist church 
and does most of my singing for the lord cub scout jack foy of 
laurel md son of a computer whiz at the national institutes of 
health and cheryl chance an editorial assistant for the us army 
who said she was late for work even as we speak 
</TEXT>
