company would not respond to collins criticism until corporate 
officials had seen the letter 
the kpi reports concluded that pan am conducted insufficient 
checks of baggage did a poor job of questioning passengers boarding 
planes and was slow to react to warnings of possible terrorist 
activity according to mrs collins 
in conclusion there are no adequate safeguards under the 
presently operating security system that would prevent a passenger 
from boarding a plane with explosives on his person or in his 
baggage whether or not he is aware of the fact the security 
company wrote 
the reports said xray examinations of luggage should be replaced 
with manual searches which were performed too infrequently 
on the whole the presently employed search techniques stand a 
low chance of discovering concealed explosive charges if at all 
the consultant wrote 
the company wrote that careful scrutiny of lostandfound baggage 
is very rare making it simple for explosives to be sent 
ownerless to a supposed destination 
at some airports including london baggage with a pan am tag 
simply placed on a conveyer belt would be loaded onto planes even 
without a registered passenger kpi said 
the consultant criticized airline employees for being too lax 
when searching the baggage of americans and of citizens of each 
airports country considering them safer 
