<TEXT>
for two decades scientists 
enjoyed a cloistered existence at this us research center 
studying wildlife in conditions as unspoiled as anywhere in the 
world 
no longer 
the mission of palmer station perched on a gravelly point 
beneath a towering glacier changed overnight when the argentine 
supply ship bahia paraiso ran aground jan 28 and spilled its cargo 
of diesel fuel just offshore 
this is changing from a place where people studied untouched 
nature longterm to a place where people study the effects of an oil 
spill longterm said margaret rubega an ornithologist from the 
university of californiairvine she was studying skuas and kelp 
gulls at the station when the wreck occurred 
as an ecosystem that was basically undisturbed its a horrible 
loss really its tragic miss rubega said 
william fraser an ornithologist from the point reyes calif 
bird observatory said there already are indications of some 
poisoning of penguins skuas cormorants and other bird species that 
populate the rocky islands around the spill 
we have no direct evidence of heavy mortality but we have 
indirect evidence he said 
scavanging giant petrels who live on the rocky islands around the 
base were feeding their newborn chicks an unusually rich diet of 
penguin meat after the spill fraser said 
what this means is you had large numbers of penguins dying 
locally 
in addition 726 pairs of polar skuas were nesting in the area 
when the spill occurred 
every single one lost their chicks frazer said 
he stressed that the evidence was not conclusive a team of 15 
us scientists has just begun more comprehensive studies 
ironically the site offers an excellent base of information for 
a beforeandafter examination of a spill the wealth of data on 
bird and marine life collected since the station went into operation 
can be used for comparison fraser said 
its a terrible disaster but its an incredible natural 
experiment 
