<TEXT>
here are some facts and figures about antarctica 
history britains capt james cook is believed to have first 
entered antarctic waters during an expedition in 177375 and he was 
followed by several other mariners who discovered land there in the 
early 1800s the american capt charles wilkes first identified it 
as a continent in 1840 when he traced 1500 miles of coastline the 
first inland expeditions were carried out by norways leonard 
kristensen and britains robert f scott and ernest shackleton in 
the late 1800s and early 1900s roald amundsen of norway reached the 
south pole in december 1911 and scott arrived a month later but his 
fourman party perished 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
geography antarctica is 51 million square miles in area larger 
than all of europe and now has been determined to have 17500 miles 
of rugged coastline its uneven surface of rock and gravel descends 
toward the center like a soup bowl under the vast weight of a 
rounded cap of ice more than a mile deep in some places the total 
volume of ice on the continent is equivalent to 72 percent of all 
water on earth the continent is divided by the transantarctic 
mountain range and includes other clusters of peaks including visson 
massif the highest at 16864 feet above sea level 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
climate the coldest continent antarticas inland temperatures 
remain almost constantly below freezing on the antarctic peninsula 
temperatures can rise above freezing during the austral summer the 
lowest reading ever at the soviet unions vostok station on july 
21 1983 was minus 892 degrees celcius there is little 
precipitation in antarctica averaging four inches a year 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
politics the continent is administered by the antarctic treaty 
signed by 12 nations in 1961 who agreed to suspend all territorial 
claims and dedicate the region to peaceful research eight other 
nations have since become voting members while 18 more enjoy 
observer status the treaty is up for review in 1991 seven nations 
make direct territorial claims to part of the continent with some 
claims overlapping other countries including the united states and 
the soviet union refuse to recognize any claims 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0250 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
an ambitious experiment to allow chinese to 
own their homes has halted in this seaside city because of 
complaints from powerful officials and austerity policies in beijing 
other experiments in housing reform throughout china are also off 
to a slow start due to the skyhigh price of living space and lack 
of confidence in the government 
the policies are in contradiction we dont know what the 
future holds said qin shiyu a housing reform official in yantai 
a breezy town in shandong province on the bohai sea 
in beijing apartments cost the equivalent of about 45 a square 
foot meaning that an average college graduate would have to save 
his total income for 70 years to buy a basic threeroom flat 
in crowded shanghai prices can be even higher 
a recent report by the official xinhua news agency said living 
space per person in a shanghai neighborhood amounted to nine by nine 
feet or 54 square feet 
and thats only for the relatively well off it said 
thousands it said were living in 216 square feet of space 
in yantai prices have been more reasonable and 1600 homes have 
been sold in about two years but 16000 families are still waiting 
for a chance to buy 
yu bingmo a worker at the yantai general synthetic leather 
factory was lucky 
in october he scraped together his life savings took out a loan 
and bought his threeroom 600squarefoot apartment or about 30 
feet by 20 feet for about 12000 yuan 3243 
it may mean a few more years of lousy cigarettes but i was 
willing to take the risk said yu 57 as he sat with his wife in 
the living room its not a palace but at least its mine 
china began housing reform in the mid1980s in an attempt to 
correct a serious housing shortage that had left millions of chinese 
urban dwellers with nowhere to live 
the plan picked up urgency over the past few years as part of 
chinas effort to reform its heavily subsidized housing system 
in chinas countryside houses are privately owned and passed 
from generation to generation but in the cities home to 40 percent 
of the countrys 11 billion people housing has been built and 
maintained by state funds and rented at rockbottom prices 
chinas housing industry is a welfare undertaking making no 
profits at all said a recent edition of the beijing review 
china also looked at private housing as a way to channel peoples 
money into the countrys infrastructure and halt spending on 
consumer goods they reasoned that less consumer spending would 
limit record high inflation of around 30 percent 
in addition reformers wanted to battle corrupt officials who use 
their power to secure bigger and better apartments for themselves 
and their friends 
in 1986 yantai and three other cities were selected as the first 
group of pilot cities for urban housing reform 
in yantai rent was raised almost 2000 percent to 124 yuan a 
square meter 3 cents a square foot to chinese accustomed to 
paying around 3 percent of their salaries for rent the jump was 
substantial 
next the housing department ordered businesses in the city to 
add a subsidy of 235 percent of each workers salary to his 
paycheck to make up for the rent increase 
as rent payments to work units increased the state cut the 
amount it gave them for housing residents were also made 
responsible for the upkeep of their homes 
youve got a broken toilet well fix it yourself said wang 
qingyuan head of the real estate management office in yantai the 
end result is that people are being made more responsible for their 
lives 
workers were encouraged to buy their houses at cutrate prices 
onetenth to onefifth of the market rate special low or 
nointerest loans were offered 
to discourage speculation resale was permitted only after five 
years 
the sales pace was quick 
but chinas economy was overheating to cut spending the state 
council chinas cabinet ordered all money received in the sales of 
housing frozen in bank accounts for two years and the ministry of 
finance clamped a 40 percent tax on those funds 
other problems were brewing 
yantai known for its clean air and fresh fish is a retirement 
area for some of chinas most powerful former officials when rents 
went up they complained some went on rent strikes others used 
connections to avoid paying 
the effect on yantais reform was deadening work units which 
own all the housing stopped selling a halt in sales meant housing 
construction stopped 
we were like a truck moving downhill and then somebody slammed 
on the brakes said one official it was a pretty big shock 
other cities like beijing and shanghai have also begun housing 
reform but to them it only means putting a few houses on the market 
their success has been even less notable than yantais 
because housing prices are so high and no attempts have been made 
to change the rent system only successful individual businessmen 
still a rarity in china are able to afford their own home 
on a recent afternoon sun xiaofeng a cab driver who makes 300 
yuan 81 a month a good deal by chinese standards strolled into 
the beijing real estate exchange 
im just curious he said ill never be able to buy a 
house not in 10000 years 
</TEXT>
