<TEXT>
here in one place you can contemplate 
18thcentury agricultural life 19thcentury industry and 
20thcentury music 
waterloo village is a restored rural village with buildings 
spanning two centuries offering the visitor a visible historic time 
chart 
houses and outbuildings in rusticated stones from the 1740s show 
how the homesteaders who settled here along the banks of the 
musconetcong river milled grain by water power and worked their 
trades as weavers tavern keepers blacksmiths apothecaries and the 
like 
iron was found in the region and by the time of the 
revolutionary war andover forge in the village was producing gun 
barrels for the continental army in 1815 brig gen john smith an 
early landowner renamed the community to celebrate wellingtons 
victory over napoleon at waterloo that year 
the opening of the 102mile morris canal in the 1830s marked the 
next era with waterloo serving as an inland port for barges 
transporting coal iron and grain from pennsylvania to the hudson 
river the barges have gone now but the towpaths remain for walking 
through forests along lakes and rivers tall victorian mansion 
houses also remain as a legacy of waterloos mid19th century 
prosperity 
waterloo declined with the coming of the railroads after the 
1840s and nearly disappeared after the market crash in 1929 but the 
abandoned village was discovered by percival leach and louis 
gualandi in the 1940s and they began its restoration the two men 
partners in a design firm solicited money for restoration and 
antiques for the 11000acre property turning it into a historical 
museum now owned jointly by the state and the nonprofit waterloo 
foundation 
music festivals are the 20thcentury contribution to waterloo 
its summer concert series began 20 years ago and since then both 
classic and popular artists have entertained more than 250000 
visitors each year 
</TEXT>
