<TEXT>
the supreme court today cleared the way for the 
partial merger of detroits two daily newspapers 
the court over two dissenting votes set aside an earlier 
postponement that had been granted by justice william j brennan 
a federal appeals court panel here voted 21 last jan 27 to 
uphold thenattorney general edwin meeses decision to allow the 
newspapers to form a joint operating agreement under the federal 
newspaper preservation act 
the 1970 law empowers the attorney general to give financially 
failing newspapers an exemption from antitrust laws 
under the joint operating agreement the detroit free press and 
the detroit news would combine their business advertising and 
production departments but maintain separate news and editorial 
staffs 
by a 54 vote last month the full appeals court refused to 
reconsider the threejudge panels january ruling 
brennan in a threeparagraph order march 4 postponing the 
merger said he was referring the matter to the full court 
a group of michigan readers and advertisers who sued to stop the 
partial merger contend that the free press a morning newspaper 
owned by knightridder inc is not a failing newspaper even though 
it lost 10 milion a year between 1981 and 1986 
the opponents calling themselves michigan citizens for an 
independent press say the free press and news which lost 50 
million in the same period were unprofitable solely because both 
papers cut prices in an unsuccessful effort to force each other out 
of business 
gannett co which owns the news is the nations largest 
newspaper publishing group knightridder is the second largest 
knightridder has threatened to close down the free press if the 
joint operating agreement is not approved 
the opponents emergency request said the agreement threatens 
the independence of daily newspapers in 25 cities where like 
detroit competing newspapers still exist 
justices harry a blackmun and john paul stevens voted to extend 
the postponment until the court considers a formal appeal by those 
who oppose the partial merger 
finally we seem to be near the point where we can assure the 
readers of the free press that their newspaper is saved said free 
press publisher david lawrence 
in other action today the court 
agreed to decide whether there is a constitutional right to 
take the hullocinogenic drug peyote as a religious practice 
the court agreed to review a ruling that oregon officials 
violated religious freedom by denying unemployment compensation to 
two men fired for using peyote at religious ceremonies 
agreed to use a new jersey case to decide whether federal 
courts may make it easier to broaden age discrimination lawsuits 
against employers 
