southland corp owner of 7eleven convenience 
stores monday reported it lost 37 millionin the fourth quarter and 
2162 million for all of last year reflecting high interest costs 
and other expenses related to its 1987 leveraged buyout 
the losses occurred despite strong operating results for its 
7eleven stores 
revenue amounted to 197 billion in the three months ended dec 
31 and 799 billion in all of 1988 
because of the buyout the seven months ended july 31 1987 were 
reported on a separate accounting basis than subsequent periods 
which means results from the two periods within 1987 cannot be added 
together to produce 1987 fullyear financial results and no 
fullyear comparisons can be made between 1987 and 1988 
southlands 1988 earnings before interest taxes depreciation 
and amortization was 4943 million including 165 million from 
divested operations the company said 
jere w thompson southlands president and chief executive 
officer called that figure the most appropriate measure of our 
progress 
were very pleased overall with the companys operating and 
financial achievements during its first full year after undergoing 
one of the largest leveraged buyouts in history thompson said in 
a prepared statement 
southland added 600 convenience stores to its 7eleven 
international operation in 1988 the division now includes nearly 
5300 stores operated by licensees and affiliates in the united 
states and 19 foreign countries 
southland operates about 7000 additional convenience stores in 
the united states and canada and owns a 50 percent interest in 
citgo petroleum corp 
the company has completed the sale of 910 operating convenience 
stores and virtually all of its other businesses scheduled for 
divestiture as part of the lbo 
