<TEXT>
owners of the seabrook nuclear power plant 
bought a bond monday to guarantee enough money to decommission the 
reactor if necessary after tests a move that could give them their 
longsought lowpower license 
the nuclear regulatory commission in an unprecedented move 
ordered seabrook owners in december to show they could come up with 
72 million to tear down and clean up the plant after the lowpower 
tests with radioactive fuel if the plant fails to overcome 
evacuationplanning and financial obstacles to a commercial license 
opponents have argued that towns in the area could not be safely 
evacuated in case of a reactor accident one of the 12 new england 
utilities that own the plant has sought bankruptcy protection becuse 
of debt associated with the plant 
the owners paid 85 million monday to aetna casualty and surety 
co of hartford conn to insure any part of the 72 million that 
the owners could not come up with themselves said seabrook 
spokesman rob williams he said aetna would refund as much as 6 
million if the plant operates commercially 
edward brown president of seabrook operator new hampshire 
yankee called the bond purchase a significant milestone for 
seabrook station 
we have now met all of the nuclear regulatory commissions 
stringent requirements to receive a lowpower license and begin 
important testing of seabrooks reactor brown said in a statement 
the nrc left it to its staff to approve the bond and issue the 
lowpower license though the commission gave opponents 10 days 
after the license is issued to seek a stay 
if the nrc staff takes a week or two to review this and then 
theres a 10day waiting period it looks like we could be in a 
position to receive lowpower in the first part of april williams 
said 
veteran plant foe robert backus lawyer for the seacoast 
antipollution league noted that the surety bond if approved is 
the last obstacle to lowpower tests at the 59 billion seabrook 
project which originally was planned for commercial operation 10 
years ago 
so its not a good day as far as im concerned backus said 
in another seabrookrelated development monday gov judd greggs 
office announced that the state will start intensive negotiations 
with lead plant owner public service co of new hampshire and its 
creditors on a bankruptcy reorganization plan for the utility 
public service sought bankruptcy protection 14 months ago because 
of debt from its 36 percent seabrook share 
gregg in a departure from unwavering state support for seabrook 
announced earlier this month he will try to block testing of the 
plant until commercial operation is assured he called it bad 
business judgment to contaminate the plant before a commercial 
license is guaranteed 
state officials said they plan to request within the next week in 
bankruptcy court that the testing be stopped 
on tuesday an nrc licensing board opens what could be the last 
round of hearings on the plants commercial license 
the atomic safety and licensing board will hold hearings for 
several months in boston on evacuation plans that seabrook developed 
for nearby massachusetts communities that refuse to cooperate 
massachusetts gov michael dukakis maintains that no evacuation 
plans could work for the crowded beaches and communities within 
seabrooks 10mile emergencyplanning zone 
